Pass setPlugins down from App.tsx through PluginList to PluginCard.

In App.tsx:
- Pass setPlugins to PluginList (in addition to or instead of onRefresh)

In PluginList.tsx:
- Accept setPlugins: React.Dispatch<React.SetStateAction<PluginState[]>> prop
- Pass it through to PluginCard

In PluginCard.tsx:
- Accept setPlugins prop
- handleToggleAll becomes:
  const handleToggleAll = (e: React.MouseEvent) => {
    e.stopPropagation();
    const newEnabled = !allEnabled;
    setPlugins(prev => prev.map(p =>
      p.name === plugin.name
        ? { ...p, tools: p.tools.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: newEnabled })) }
        : p
    ));
    void setAllToolsEnabled(plugin.name, newEnabled).catch(() => {
      setPlugins(prev => prev.map(p =>
        p.name === plugin.name
          ? { ...p, tools: p.tools.map(t => ({ ...t, enabled: !newEnabled })) }
          : p
      ));
      showToggleError('Failed to toggle all tools');
    });
  };
- handleToggleTool becomes similar: optimistic flip of the specific tool, revert on error
- Remove .then(onRefresh) chains
- If onRefresh is no longer used anywhere, remove it from the component chain. But check if loadPlugins is still needed in App.tsx for plugins.changed invalidation — it is, but it doesn't need to be passed as onRefresh to PluginCard.

Note: The plugin prop to PluginCard is derived from the plugins state array in App.tsx, so setPlugins updates will cause re-renders with fresh data automatically.

Create e2e/side-panel-data-flow.e2e.ts. Follow the patterns in e2e/side-panel-live-update.e2e.ts for setup.

The test file should import from fixtures.ts and helpers.ts. Use the same getExtensionId and openSidePanel helpers (copy them or extract to helpers.ts).

Test structure:
test.describe('Side panel data flow — connection status', () => {
  test('shows connected status and transitions on server stop/restart', async () => {
    // 1. Start MCP server with e2e-test plugin
    // 2. Launch extension context
    // 3. Open side panel
    // 4. Verify 'Connected' text visible
    // 5. Verify plugin card visible (e.g., 'E2E Test')
    // 6. Kill MCP server
    // 7. Verify 'Disconnected' text appears (within 30s — pong timeout is 5s + reconnect backoff)
    // 8. Verify plugin list is cleared (no plugin cards visible)
    // 9. Restart MCP server on same port
    // 10. Verify 'Connected' text reappears
    // 11. Verify plugin card reappears
  });
});

Use expect(page.locator('text=Connected')).toBeVisible() and expect(page.locator('text=Disconnected')).toBeVisible() with appropriate timeouts.

For restart: use startMcpServer with the same configDir to start a new server on the same port. The offscreen document's reconnect logic will find it.

IMPORTANT: The side panel file needs to be added to the tsconfig that covers E2E tests. Check if e2e/ files are already covered by a tsconfig. Look at tsconfig.configs.json or the root tsconfig.json project references.

Add to e2e/side-panel-data-flow.e2e.ts in a new test.describe block.

The tab state dots in the side panel use these CSS classes (from PluginCard.tsx):
- ready: 'bg-emerald-400' (green)
- unavailable: 'bg-amber-400' (amber)
- closed: 'bg-red-400' (red)

Test structure:
test.describe('Side panel data flow — tab state changes', () => {
  test('tab state dot updates when matching tab opens and closes', async () => {
    // 1. Start MCP server with e2e-test plugin, start test server
    // 2. Launch extension context
    // 3. Wait for extension connected
    // 4. Open side panel
    // 5. Verify plugin card is visible with 'E2E Test'
    // 6. Verify the red dot (bg-red-400) is visible (tab closed state)
    //    Use: page.locator('.bg-red-400') inside the plugin card area
    // 7. Open a new tab to testServer.url
    // 8. Wait for the green dot (bg-emerald-400) to appear (tab ready state)
    //    The adapter needs to be injected and isReady() must return true
    //    This may take a few seconds — use toBeVisible({ timeout: 15_000 })
    // 9. Close the matching tab
    // 10. Verify the red dot (bg-red-400) reappears
  });
});

This test depends on US-001 (tab.stateChanged forwarding to side panel). Without US-001, the side panel would only update on the next fetchConfigState() round-trip, which is triggered by plugins.changed (not by tab events). With US-001, the tab state dot updates immediately via the direct push.

The test server must be started so the e2e-test plugin has a matching URL to target. Use the test server from fixtures.ts.

IMPORTANT: Need to set up the adapter symlink between config dir and extension dir, same as in side-panel-live-update.e2e.ts.

