The invocation animation in ToolRow.tsx:
- Active tools get the class 'animate-tool-pulse' on the row div
- Active tools show a spinning div with class 'animate-spin'

Test structure:
test.describe('Side panel data flow — tool invocation animation', () => {
  test('shows spinner during tool call and removes it after', async () => {
    // 1. Full setup: MCP server + test server + extension + MCP client
    // 2. Open test app tab, wait for adapter injection and ready state
    // 3. Open side panel
    // 4. Wait for plugin card to appear
    // 5. Click the plugin card to expand it (click the button[aria-expanded])
    // 6. Verify tool rows are visible
    // 7. Use the test server to add a delay to tool responses (e.g., 3 seconds)
    //    The test server has a /control endpoint — check if there's a way to add delay
    //    If not, just call a tool and check quickly
    // 8. Call a tool via mcpClient.callTool() in parallel with checking the DOM
    //    Use Promise.all([toolCall, spinnerCheck]) where spinnerCheck polls for .animate-spin
    // 9. After tool completes, verify .animate-spin is gone
  });
});

The tricky part is timing — the tool call may complete very fast. The e2e-test plugin's get_status tool returns immediately. To observe the spinner:
- Option A: Use Promise.race — start the tool call, immediately check for spinner, don't wait for tool to complete
- Option B: Use the test server's delay mechanism if available
- Option C: Just verify the spinner appears at some point during execution using polling

Check the test server (e2e/test-server.ts) for any delay/slow response mechanism. If the test server has no delay mechanism, the tool may complete too fast to observe the spinner. In that case, the test can verify the animate-tool-pulse class briefly appears using a Playwright polling assertion or by slowing down the response.

Looking at test-server.ts, there's a 'mode' system that controls responses. Check if there's an 'errorMode' or 'slowMode'. If not, this test may need to rely on quick polling or use a different approach.

Alternative approach: Instead of testing the visual animation, test that the activeTools state is updated by checking the DOM class. Use page.locator('.animate-tool-pulse') and verify it appears during the tool call.
